{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523025"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13868"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13868"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.41,0.38,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48451"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6485"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33368"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48451"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman is admitted to the surgical ward following an elective total knee replacement three days ago. As the duty intern, you are called to review her because she has developed a fever. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for 100 mg aspirin daily, which was commenced day one post-operatively, with sequential compression device (SCD) use for deep vein thrombosis prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her temperature is 38.3\u00b0C, pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and SpO2 96% on room air. She appears uncomfortable but not in acute distress. Her surgical wound looks clean and dry. Chest auscultation reveals slightly decreased breath sounds at the left base. Her calf is slightly tender but not swollen. She denies any chest pain or shortness of breath. CXR was performed and reported to be normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her fever?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical site infection","Drug-induced fever","Pulmonary embolism","Atelectasis","Urinary tract infection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most likely cause of fever is \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolism (PE)\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has several risk factors for venous thromboembolism, including recent surgery and relative immobilisation. The tachycardia, tachypnea, and decreased breath sounds at the left base are consistent with PE. While she denies chest pain or shortness of breath, PE can present with non-specific symptoms, and fever is a known manifestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical site infection\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given that the wound looks clean and dry, and it\u0027s relatively early (three days post-op) for a significant surgical site infection to develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-induced fever\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility, but there\u0027s no mention of new medications that commonly cause drug fever. Enoxaparin is not typically associated with drug fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtelectasis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever in the immediate postoperative period, but it\u0027s less likely to be the sole cause of fever three days after surgery, especially with the other clinical features present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E is always a consideration in hospitalized patients, especially those with indwelling catheters. However, there are no specific urinary symptoms mentioned, and the other clinical features point more strongly towards PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of considering non-infective causes of fever in postoperative patients, particularly thromboembolic events. A thorough evaluation, including consideration of PE, is crucial in managing postoperative fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-infective causes of fever that may need to be considered include thrombus (PE, DVT), drug effects, cancer, connective tissue diseases and postoperative atelectasis.","A thorough history and physical examination are crucial in evaluating fever of unknown origin.","Recent surgery and immobilization are risk factors for venous thromboembolism."],"references":["Nucifora G, Badano L, Hysko F, Allocca G, Gianfagna P, Fioretti P. Pulmonary Embolism and Fever. Circulation. 2007;115(6):e173-e6. Available at: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/full/10.1161/circulationaha.106.674358"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33368"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13868"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33368"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-12T11:24:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-15T17:12:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6485"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48451"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attribute